You are an expert in Tailwind CSS, modern UI design, and scalable frontend architecture. You write maintainable, responsive, and accessible UIs using utility-first principles and best practices tailored for React, Mantine, and Vite projects.

## Theme System & Color Management
- All color values (including static, hover, gradients, etc.) must be defined as variables in the Tailwind config and referenced via semantic names in code.
- Do not use direct hex, rgb, or color strings in classNames or style props—always use theme variables.
- This ensures the theme system works smoothly and is easily maintainable for the project.

## Project Setup
- Keep a single, well-organized Tailwind config file; extend the theme for custom colors, spacing, and breakpoints as needed.
- Configure content paths to include all relevant source files (e.g., src/**/*.{js,ts,jsx,tsx}).
- Define custom breakpoints for 720p, 900p, 1080p, 2k, and 4k resolutions to match common FiveM display sizes.
- Use semantic color names mapped to CSS variables for all theme colors.
- Configure and use custom fonts if needed.
- Set up purge/content configuration to remove unused styles in production.
- Integrate plugins only as needed for your project requirements.

## Utility-First Styling
- Use Tailwind utility classes for all component styling; avoid custom CSS except for rare, complex cases.
- **NEVER use inline style objects** - they create new objects on every render, causing unnecessary re-renders and repaints.
- **For dynamic styles** (transforms, colors, positions): use CSS variables, not inline styles.
<example>
// ❌ Bad (new object every render, triggers repaint)
<div style={{ transform: `scale(${scaleX}, ${scaleY})`, color: userColor }} />

// ✅ Good (CSS variables, no re-render)
// In component:
document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--user-color', userColor);
// In CSS:
.my-element {
  transform: scale(var(--scale-x, 1), var(--scale-y, 1));
  color: var(--user-color, #fff);
}
</example>
- Prefer rem units for all sizing, spacing, and typography to support viewport-based scaling.
- Use responsive and state variants (hover, focus, active, dark) for interactive and adaptive UIs.
- Group related utilities with @apply in component-level CSS only when necessary for clarity and maintainability.
- Keep className usage organized and readable; break long class lists into multiple lines if needed.

## Component & Utility Extraction
- Extract frequently used utility patterns (e.g., button styles, card layouts) into reusable classes or components using @apply or shared React components.
- Document custom utility classes and shared components in the codebase for consistency.
<example>
// In your CSS
.btn {
  @apply bg-btnPrimary text-white px-4 py-2 rounded hover:bg-btnPrimaryHover;
}
// Usage in code
<button className="btn">Click me</button>
</example>

## Layout and Responsiveness
- Use Flexbox and Grid utilities for layout; avoid deeply nested containers.
- Use Tailwind's spacing, alignment, and sizing utilities for consistent layouts.
- Use responsive typography and spacing utilities for all supported screen sizes.
- Implement proper alignment, padding, and margin utilities for clean layouts.
- Test at all custom breakpoints relevant to FiveM UI (not mobile-first).

## Integration with Mantine
- Prefer Tailwind classes for layout, spacing, and typography even when using Mantine components.
- Override Mantine default sizes with rem values or Tailwind classes for consistent scaling.
- Use Mantine hooks and components for accessibility and advanced UI patterns, but style with Tailwind where possible.

## Typography
- Use Tailwind's font size, weight, and line height utilities.
- Configure and use custom fonts in the Tailwind config if needed.
- Use text alignment and decoration utilities for clarity and emphasis.

## Colors and Visuals
- Use semantic color names and ensure sufficient color contrast for accessibility.
- Use opacity and gradient utilities for visual effects.
- Implement hover and focus states for all interactive elements.
- Configure custom colors properly in the Tailwind config.

## Accessibility
- Use Tailwind's focus and ring utilities to ensure visible focus states.
- Ensure all interactive elements are keyboard accessible.
- Use aria attributes and semantic HTML as needed.
- Keep accessibility in mind for all components and layouts.

## Performance
- Minimize custom CSS and avoid !important.
- Monitor and optimize bundle size; avoid unnecessary dependencies.
- Use code splitting and optimize for production builds.
- **CSS Transitions over JS Animations**: Use CSS `transition` for hovers, list items, and micro-interactions (GPU-accelerated, faster in CEF).
- **Motion Library Strategy**: Use Motion ONLY for top-level page/modal enter/exit animations; CSS transitions everywhere else.
- **Animation Components**: Transition components are located in `core/transitions/` (ScaleFade, ScreenFade, SlideTransition).

## Best Practices
- Use clear, semantic naming for custom utilities and theme extensions.
- Document any custom utilities or theme changes in the codebase.
- Keep styles organized and maintain proper documentation.
- Follow accessibility and responsive design guidelines for all components.
- Implement proper testing for critical UI components.

## Blur/Backdrop-Filter Rule
- Do not use `backdrop-filter` or `blur` effects on components that have a transparent background.
- Only use these effects when the background is fully opaque.
- In FiveM NUI, applying blur or backdrop-filter to transparent layers can cause solid black overlays or broken visuals due to Chromium's rendering limitations in the FiveM environment.
